# Toronto Rising ‚Äî Linear tracking (primary responsibility)

**Linear is a primary source of truth for project state**, alongside the codebase. Agents must treat Linear synchronization as part of completing work ‚Äî not an optional follow-up.

## Authoritative surfaces

| Surface | Role |
| --- | --- |
| **Linear** (`Toronto Rising` team, `TOR-*`) | Status, ownership, history, bug anchors for shipped features |
| [`.dev/RUNNING TASKLIST.md`](../../.dev/RUNNING%20TASKLIST.md) | Planned work + **`## Focus`** stack rank; every bullet has `_(TOR-XX)_` |
| [`.dev/INBOX.md`](../../.dev/INBOX.md) | Quick capture (`bug` / `intent` / `idea`); **not** authoritative for status until triaged |
| **Code + `.dev/` docs** | Implementation truth; must match Done issues |

When these diverge, **reconcile immediately** (update Linear and/or tasklist to match code reality).

## Human-readable Linear references

Whenever an agent writes a `TOR-XXX` id in chat, summaries, Focus **Deferred** lines, or handoffs, **always add a few words of context** from the issue/tasklist title. Never bare ids alone.

- Bad: `Deferred: TOR-139, TOR-140`
- Good: `Deferred: TOR-139 (scenes panel trim + library grid), TOR-140 (sound panel text)`

Tables with a dedicated title/description column satisfy this for rows in that table only; **inline lists still need labels on every id**.

## Precedence vs priority

**Do not conflate work order with importance.**

| Axis | Surfaces | Agent rule |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Precedence** | **Focus** stack, **Deferred this cycle**, Linear **`blocks` / `blockedBy`** | ‚ÄúDo A before B‚Äù ‚Äî use **`blockedBy` liberally** when B should wait for A (hard or soft sequencing). Author removes wrong blocks in Linear. |
| **Priority** | Linear **Priority** only | Intrinsic urgency/importance when scheduled. **Deferral from Focus does not imply Low.** Open bugs elsewhere do **not** auto-downgrade unrelated issues. |

### Linear relationship types (when to use which)

| Relation | Use for |
| --- | --- |
| **`parentId` / sub-issue** | Hierarchy ‚Äî feature belongs under epic or parent feature |
| **`blockedBy` / `blocks`** | Sequencing ‚Äî prerequisite should finish first (**liberal use OK** for ‚Äúshould complete before‚Äù) |
| **`relatedTo`** | Same theme or context ‚Äî **no** implied order |

**Agent guardrails:** One direction per sequencing pair (A blocks B, not both ways). Prefer **`parentId`** for decomposition, not blocking. Avoid circular **`blockedBy`** chains. When deferring inbox work, propose **`blockedBy`** + priority separately in **Back-burner proposal**.

### Anti-gridlock (avoid block proliferation)

Liberal blocking is for **auditable sequencing**, not a dense dependency mesh. Gridlock looks like: every open bug **`blockedBy`**-links to every deferred feature, deferred features block each other, or transitive chains where A blocks B blocks C when A‚ÜíC would suffice.

**Do:**

- Attach blockers **to the waiting issue only** (star pattern): `TOR-143 (phase redesign) blockedBy TOR-141 (E2E playbooks)` ‚Äî prerequisites do not block each other unless truly required.
- Keep **`blockedBy` lists short and direct** ‚Äî typically **1‚Äì6** prerequisites on the dependent issue; name each with a label in the Back-burner proposal.
- Block on **concrete gate issues** (Focus bugs, regression harness, a specific refactor) ‚Äî not ‚Äúeverything in Backlog.‚Äù
- Use **`relatedTo`** when issues share context but order is flexible.
- **Remove obsolete `blocks` relations** when a prerequisite is **Done** or deferral is lifted (see Focus step 5 in DEVELOPMENT_WORKFLOW).

**Do not:**

- Make **deferred peers block each other** (e.g. TOR-139 blocks TOR-140) unless one genuinely depends on the other‚Äôs output.
- Add **transitive duplicates** when the chain is already implied (if B blocks C, do not also make A block C when B already blocks C and A blocks B ‚Äî pick the minimal set).
- Turn **Focus stack order** into a full mesh ‚Äî Focus + **Deferred this cycle** already express cycle precedence; `blockedBy` should capture **specific** ‚Äúwait for these‚Äù gates, not re-link the entire board.

If a Back-burner proposal would add **more than ~6** blockers on one issue, stop and justify in chat ‚Äî or propose a **single** umbrella blocker (e.g. ‚Äúafter TOR-141 (E2E playbooks)‚Äù) instead.

## Inbox back-burner confirmation (`/tr-inbox`)

Before an item **promoted from INBOX** is excluded from Focus or marked **Deferred this cycle**:

1. Present a **Back-burner proposal**: `TOR-XXX (label)`, proposed Focus treatment, **proposed blockers** (labeled), **proposed Linear priority** (separate from deferral), and rationale.
2. **Wait for author confirmation** before writing deferrals, **`blockedBy`** links, or priority changes ‚Äî unless the author explicitly overrode in the same session.

**Never** set Linear **Low** on a deferred inbox item unless the author confirms low *importance* ‚Äî not merely ‚Äúnot this cycle.‚Äù

## Capture vs scheduled work

- **Quick note:** one line in [`.dev/INBOX.md`](../../.dev/INBOX.md) under **Active** (prefixes optional).
- **Triage:** **`/tr-inbox`** (or ‚Äúprocess the inbox‚Äù) ‚Üí Phase 1: park unclear items in **Needs clarification** with `?` bullets (answers inline as `Answer:`); Phase 2: promote when every `?` is answered ‚Äî see [DEVELOPMENT_WORKFLOW ¬ß Inbox](../../.dev/DEVELOPMENT%20WORKFLOW.md#inbox-capture--triage).

## Agent workflow (every task)

1. **Before starting** ‚Äî Search Linear for related `TOR-*` issues; read matching tasklist bullet if present; skim INBOX Active if overlap is likely.
2. **When starting** ‚Äî Set issue **In Progress**; confirm tasklist bullet has the correct `_(TOR-XX)_`. Prompt the author once to rename the Cursor chat to **`TOR-XX ‚Äî short title`** (agents cannot rename chats programmatically ‚Äî see `.cursor/commands/tr-start.md` ¬ß Agent chat title).
3. **When finishing** ‚Äî Mark **Done** (or **Canceled** if descoped) with a comment: what changed, key files, verification, commit refs. Update tasklist `[ ]` ‚Üí `[x]` if applicable. Reference `TOR-XX` in commit body when committing. **`living-doc` issues:** baseline may be `[x]` on tasklist but issue stays **In Progress** ‚Äî see ¬ß Living documentation.

   **Deferred resurfacing (gate closes):** When the closed issue is on **Focus**, listed in **Deferred this cycle**, or is a **`blockedBy` prerequisite** for other open work:
   - Remove stale **`blockedBy`** on Linear dependents whose prerequisites are now **Done** or **Canceled**.
   - Skim **Deferred this cycle** and Linear dependents (issues that **`blockedBy`** the closed id); note any that should **resurface** (unblocked or named in Deferred).
   - In the **Done** comment or session chat, **propose** (do not auto-apply) Focus or priority changes ‚Äî a short labeled list (`TOR-XXX (title)`), typically 1‚Äì3 items. **Inbox-promoted deferrals** still need author OK before moving into Focus (see ¬ß Inbox back-burner confirmation).
4. **Commits during work** ‚Äî After each logical unit, commit **without asking**; never prompt ‚Äúwant me to commit?‚Äù (always yes). See `.cursorrules` ¬ß Git Commits.
5. **When discovering new work** ‚Äî INBOX one-liner if capture-only; otherwise create Linear issue in the correct **domain project**, add `source:tasklist` if from tasklist, append `_(TOR-XX)_` to tasklist, set **In Progress** if starting immediately.
6. **When finding bugs on shipped features** ‚Äî Create a **Bug** issue; `relatedTo` the original **Done** feature issue. Do not reopen unrelated Done issues.
7. **Inbox triage** ‚Äî On ‚Äúprocess the inbox‚Äù: Phase 1 park + `?` in INBOX (author replies **`Answer:`** inline); Phase 2 promote when answered.
8. **What‚Äôs next** ‚Äî On ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs next‚Äù / ‚Äúprioritize the backlog‚Äù: read **Focus** in RUNNING TASKLIST, cross-check Linear Bugs + In Progress, recommend one item; update Focus; set Linear **priority** on intrinsic importance; add **`blockedBy`** for sequencing ‚Äî do not downgrade unrelated priorities because bugs exist.
9. **Inbox + prioritize** ‚Äî On **`/tr-inbox`**: triage + refresh **Focus** + Linear **priority** and **`blockedBy`** per `.cursor/commands/tr-inbox.md`.

## Domain projects

Use domain projects (not legacy Phase 1/2/3): Foundation & Tooling, Synchronization & State, Dice & Rolls, Scenes & Chronicle, Lighting & Camera, NPC & Spotlight, Soundscape & Audio, UI & HUD, Character Sheets, Players & Connection, Table Objects, Agent Reviews & Quality, Out of Scope (Workshop).

Parent epics: TOR-30 (Foundation) through TOR-43 (Workshop). Attach new issues under the matching epic via `parentId` when applicable.

## Labels

- `Feature`, `Improvement`, or `Bug`
- `source:tasklist` when the item originates from RUNNING TASKLIST
- `module:*` matching the domain (`module:dice`, `module:conditions`, etc.)
- **`workshop-only`** ‚Äî author-owned work outside the repo (TTS save, art, external tools); **agents do not implement**; keep issue **Backlog**/**Todo**, not **Canceled**
- **`human-gate`** (when on team) ‚Äî same agent skip rule; description must include `## Human gate` with the author‚Äôs next step
- **`living-doc`** ‚Äî documentation that must stay current when related code changes; issue stays **In Progress** (do not mark **Done** when only the baseline shipped)

### Human-gated vs Canceled

**Never** set **Canceled** on live author-owned work. **Canceled** = superseded, duplicate, or explicit descope. Deferral from Focus ‚âÝ Canceled. See `DEVELOPMENT_WORKFLOW.md` ¬ß Human-gated work.

### Living documentation (`living-doc`)

Use for manuals/playbooks/registries that are **never ‚Äúfinished‚Äù** (e.g. **TOR-141** E2E playbooks under [`.dev/E2E Playbooks/`](../../.dev/E2E%20Playbooks/README.md)).

| When | Agent rule |
| --- | --- |
| Baseline shipped | Comment on issue + tasklist `[x]` for baseline bullet; keep issue **In Progress** + `living-doc` |
| Related code changes | Update playbook/docs in the **same PR**; optional short Linear comment |
| ‚ÄúClose‚Äù request | Only **Done** if docs retired or replaced by automation; else keep open |

**TOR-141** is the anchor for manual E2E verification ‚Äî not Focus stack, not Done.

